00:00:20.697 --> 00:00:22.030
HARVEY: Good evening, everybody.

00:00:22.030 --> 00:00:23.850
I'd like to welcome you to MIT.

00:00:23.850 --> 00:00:27.190
My name's Mark Harvey,
and I'm teaching here

00:00:27.190 --> 00:00:28.920
in the music program.

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:31.090
And this semester
we have a course

00:00:31.090 --> 00:00:33.850
called Musical Improvisation.

00:00:33.850 --> 00:00:37.060
And thanks to our music section
as well as the alumni class

00:00:37.060 --> 00:00:40.010
funds program, we were able
to bring in some distinguished

00:00:40.010 --> 00:00:41.410
improvisers.

00:00:41.410 --> 00:00:43.652
We've had two of these,
a series of four.

00:00:43.652 --> 00:00:44.610
We've had two of these.

00:00:44.610 --> 00:00:48.280
We have tonight, and then we
have one more in early May.

00:00:48.280 --> 00:00:50.869
Let me just say a couple
words about our visitors

00:00:50.869 --> 00:00:51.410
this evening.

00:00:51.410 --> 00:00:54.410
We have Neil Leonard, who's
been a long time friend,

00:00:54.410 --> 00:00:56.640
and Robin Eubanks over here.

00:00:56.640 --> 00:00:58.860
Neil came to our
class on Monday,

00:00:58.860 --> 00:01:00.120
and we had a great time.

00:01:00.120 --> 00:01:04.030
And so this is a
furthering, an enrichment

00:01:04.030 --> 00:01:05.089
of what we're studying.

00:01:05.089 --> 00:01:07.380
And now it's a chance for
all of you to engage in this.

00:01:07.380 --> 00:01:09.500
So you can see by
their bios, they're

00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:13.090
very distinguished world
travelers, master improvisers.

00:01:13.090 --> 00:01:15.300
So without further
ado, Neil Leonard.

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:16.728
Robin Eubanks.

00:01:16.728 --> 00:01:18.664
[AUDIENCE APPLAUSE]

00:01:22.536 --> 00:01:24.000
LEONARD: Thank you, Mark.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.156
It's wonderful to be
here at MIT this evening.

00:01:27.156 --> 00:01:30.016
I'm very pleased to
have the opportunity

00:01:30.016 --> 00:01:33.904
to play again with the
great Robin Eubanks.

00:01:33.904 --> 00:01:36.820
I'm going to play three
pieces, [INAUDIBLE] pieces,

00:01:36.820 --> 00:01:41.210
and the first two were created
under very peculiar or unique

00:01:41.210 --> 00:01:42.100
circumstances.

00:01:42.100 --> 00:01:49.140
One was at the invitation of
a conference on sonification

00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:50.965
in Washington, DC a
couple of years ago.

00:01:50.965 --> 00:01:53.570
And I did a piece with
a couple of my students

00:01:53.570 --> 00:01:57.125
that involved data that
was collected from the sun.

00:01:57.125 --> 00:02:01.480
And so we made a piece of
music out of celestial data.

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:07.300
And that's the first piece
called Nocturnal Remix.

00:02:07.300 --> 00:02:09.990
The second piece
is a piece which

00:02:09.990 --> 00:02:14.923
I created at the invitation
of an art collector

00:02:14.923 --> 00:02:17.335
in Italy, Gianni
Bolongaro who asked me

00:02:17.335 --> 00:02:20.770
if I would record the
sounds of a sculpture

00:02:20.770 --> 00:02:25.410
by an artist named
Jannis Kounellis

00:02:25.410 --> 00:02:29.820
And I began a piece, which went
through several renditions.

00:02:29.820 --> 00:02:32.800
And what you'll hear
are the sounds recorded

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:35.640
in his sculpture park,
an Italian vocalist

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:41.705
from Mount Vesuvius in
Naples, and the third piece

00:02:41.705 --> 00:02:46.227
is an improvisation on a song
that you'll probably recognize.

00:02:46.227 --> 00:02:47.560
I won't announce that right now.

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:48.552
Thank you.

