01:04:34.810 --> 01:04:38.430
LEONARD: We are going to
finish with a piece together.

01:04:38.430 --> 01:04:42.268
Does anybody know
what a pregonero is?

01:04:42.268 --> 01:04:45.030
EUBANKS: A what?

01:04:45.030 --> 01:04:46.755
LEONARD: A pregonero.

01:04:46.755 --> 01:04:48.000
ROBIN: Spanish

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:53.291
LEONARD: A pregonero is a street
vendor, who lives in Cuba.

01:04:53.291 --> 01:04:54.790
Actually they're
all over the world.

01:04:54.790 --> 01:05:00.420
But the ones that I
know live in Cuba.

01:05:00.420 --> 01:05:06.510
And for the past maybe 50 years,
their practice was not allowed.

01:05:06.510 --> 01:05:08.940
And as of a couple years
ago, if you found yourself

01:05:08.940 --> 01:05:15.500
in Cuba sitting in
your in-laws patio,

01:05:15.500 --> 01:05:22.630
you would begin to hear these
people selling ajo, garlic,

01:05:22.630 --> 01:05:27.900
soja, onions, exterminators
who could kill

01:05:27.900 --> 01:05:37.880
bed bugs, mice, mothers-in-law--
I didn't try them-- car alarms.

01:05:37.880 --> 01:05:39.170
The whole deal.

01:05:39.170 --> 01:05:43.520
This was everything you ever
needed sold door-to-door.

01:05:43.520 --> 01:05:47.030
There was no advertising,
no Internet, no billboards,

01:05:47.030 --> 01:05:49.570
no what advertisers,
no handbills.

01:05:49.570 --> 01:05:54.100
Just people roaming the
streets selling their stuff.

01:05:54.100 --> 01:06:02.270
And in the last year as
they came back instantly,

01:06:02.270 --> 01:06:05.820
I invited them to
do some pieces.

01:06:05.820 --> 01:06:07.563
And some of them
were installations,

01:06:07.563 --> 01:06:10.630
and some were performances.

01:06:10.630 --> 01:06:12.920
Probably the most
notable performance

01:06:12.920 --> 01:06:17.709
was I decided that I don't
have an interest in going

01:06:17.709 --> 01:06:20.000
to somebody else's country
and telling them what to do.

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:23.520
But I thought in Cuba they
needed an American Idol

01:06:23.520 --> 01:06:25.580
for the pregoneros.

01:06:25.580 --> 01:06:32.437
And so I staged an American
Idol for the pregoneros,

01:06:32.437 --> 01:06:36.930
an Idol of the Americas,
and invited the pregoneros

01:06:36.930 --> 01:06:40.915
and gave prizes for the most
musical pregon, the most poetic

01:06:40.915 --> 01:06:48.060
pregon, the pregonero who was
the most gifted and innovative

01:06:48.060 --> 01:06:49.900
for promoting contemporary art.

01:06:49.900 --> 01:06:51.980
We made that category.

01:06:51.980 --> 01:06:56.895
And national television picked
it up and had the pregoneros

01:06:56.895 --> 01:07:00.860
on national television with
a jury that I selected.

01:07:00.860 --> 01:07:02.670
This project keeps on going.

01:07:02.670 --> 01:07:06.720
And the next stop is
the Venice biennial,

01:07:06.720 --> 01:07:08.775
where my wife and
I have been invited

01:07:08.775 --> 01:07:12.302
to participate in the Cuban
pavilion of the Venice biennial

01:07:12.302 --> 01:07:13.230
in May.

01:07:13.230 --> 01:07:18.615
But when I thought of what I
could write for Robin that he

01:07:18.615 --> 01:07:21.990
and I could play, well I still
couldn't get these pregoneros

01:07:21.990 --> 01:07:22.740
out of my mind.

01:07:22.740 --> 01:07:28.130
So we're going to perform
a short suite of pieces

01:07:28.130 --> 01:07:30.380
and in this you'll
hear the voice of one

01:07:30.380 --> 01:07:38.260
of these pregoneros and
a lot play with the song

01:07:38.260 --> 01:07:39.610
that this person sings.

01:07:39.610 --> 01:07:43.175
So this piece is
called Pregones that I

01:07:43.175 --> 01:07:44.660
wrote for Robin and myself.

01:07:44.660 --> 01:07:46.145
Thank you.

